Code used for the overview

Moraes, L. S. C. et al.

2025-01-21

Here are all the code we used to modify the dataset, build graphs and perform the analysis.

If you wish, it is possible run this code with the dataset in the Suplemmentary Material.

The packages used:

packages <- c("openxlsx", "tidyverse", "patchwork", "egg", "scales", "ggsci", "bipartite", "qgraph", "networkD3", "igraph", "paletteer", "sf", "ggforce")

install_and_load_packages <- function(packages) {
  for(package in packages) {
    if(!require(package, character.only = TRUE)) {
      install.packages(package)
      library(package, character.only = TRUE)
    }
  }
}

install_and_load_packages(packages)

Data import and organization

Loading the data:

elect <- read.xlsx("Elected articles.xlsx", startRow = 2)

Removing collected variables that:

1 - Are unimportant for this work (colunm \(2\) = times cited; \(4\) = Web of Science category; \(5\) = Research field; \(6\) = Type of publication - are all scientific articles; \(7\) = Authors; \(55\) = Observations);

2 - Are probably inaccurate (\(42\) = Host specialization; \(46\) = Host size, in centimeters).

all_data <- elect[, -c(2, 4:7, 42, 46, 55)]

Simplifying variable names and selecting them:

data <- all_data  |>  
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)  |>  
  dplyr::rename( 
    source = Source.Title, 
    pphy = Parasite.phylum, 
    pclass = Parasite.class, 
    porder = Parasite.order, 
    pfamily = Parasite.family,

    psp = Parasite.species,

    repro = Reproduction, 
    pstyle =  Parasite.specialization, 
    kind = Euc.proc.or.virus,
    methodology = Identification.methodology, 
    host.type = Life.stage,
    site = Infection.site, 
    hphy = Invaded.host.phylum, 
    hclass = Invaded.host.class, 
    horder = Invaded.host.order, 
    hfamily = Invaded.host.family, 
    hgenus = Invaded.host.genus, 
    hsp = Invaded.host.species,
    invaded.host.origin = Invaded.host.indigenous.to,

  )  |>  
  dplyr::select( 
    ID, Year, source, Native.host, pphy, pclass, porder, pfamily, pgen, psp, porigin, Life.cycle, repro, pstyle, N.host.orders, N.host.families, Ecto.or.Endo, methodology, host.type, site, hphy, hclass, horder, hfamily, hgenus, hsp, invaded.host.origin, original.host.continent, host.feeding, status, htroph, Migrant, shchooling, ambiguous, ambstudy, lab, factor.ind, Spillmode, continent, country, meltdown, Invaded.area
  )

Simplifying categorical values (levels) of the variable factor.ind, which stands for “factor inducing invasions”:

data$factor.ind <- gsub("(Eel.*|eel.*|fish farm.*)", "Pisciculture", data$factor.ind)
data$factor.ind <- gsub("fisherman", "Fisherman", data$factor.ind)
data$factor.ind <- gsub("(Not known|Not mentioned|Unknow)", "Not mentioned or unknown", data$factor.ind)
data$factor.ind <- gsub(".*rism", "Aquarism", data$factor.ind)
data$factor.ind <- gsub(".*ol", "Biological control", data$factor.ind)

Changing the \(?\) symbol for “Unkown” in other variables:

data$repro <- gsub("\\?", "Unknown", data$repro)
data$host.feeding <- gsub("\\?", "Unknown", data$host.feeding)
data$htroph <- gsub("\\?", "Unknown", data$htroph)
data$Migrant <- gsub("\\?", "Unknown", data$Migrant)
data$shchooling <- gsub("\\?", "Unknown", data$shchooling)

Regressions

Here, we performed the regressions to understand the tendency of publications along the years.

It was necessary to control the amount of articles found for the review, by the amount of articles published in biology-related areas indexed in the Web of Science and Scopus databases.

We considered only the years where articles elected for this review were published. The numbers were all manually collected.

Number of articles published for Web of Science:

correctionWOS <- c(1313, 2428, 4640, 5479, 5427, 5583, 5760, 6067, 7731, 21240, 21723, 23767, 25595, 27104, 29623, 33014, 31921, 31906, 35001, 35242, 37878, 38332, 41176, 47025, 52926, 56692, 62755, 63681, 70639, 71357, 76191, 79482, 85068, 93098, 99055, 121026, 140964, 163793, 178630)

Number of articles published for Scopus:

correctionSCO <- c(18795, 23260, 29303, 35192, 35086, 36097, 38307, 41139, 44738, 46279, 48478, 52297, 55100, 74972, 78886, 79767, 80854, 83581, 85594, 90711, 94879, 99441, 110686, 122382, 134657, 144867, 153702, 162468, 179915, 189544, 201072, 205702, 214796, 214526, 222004, 231622, 239857, 263837, 284272)

I summed both corrections. There are probably some duplicates between databases, but the number of articles indexed in Scopus is so large that I could just subtract from Scopus the number of articles encountered in Web of Science, that it would not change the regression plot.

correction.full <- correctionSCO + correctionWOS

Creating a new column with the correction:

reg_data_articles <- data_articles  |>  
  mutate(N = Freq/correction.full)

Function used to turn all values into scientific notation:

scientific_10 <- function(x) {
  parse(text = gsub("e", " %*% 10^", scales::scientific_format()(x)))
}

Performing the linear regression, and showing the results:

li.reg <- ggplot(reg_data_articles, aes(x = Var1, y = N)) +
  geom_point(size= 1.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, colour="skyblue", fill="lightblue") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scientific_10, breaks = c(0, 2*10^-5, 3*10^-5, 4*10^-5, 5*10^-5, 6*10^-5, 7*10^-5)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1975, 2020, 5), labels = seq(1975, 2020, 5)) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 15) +
  labs (title = "a)", 
        x= NULL, 
        y= "Number of articles controlled by\nthe total number of articles in WoS and Scopus\n") +
  theme(text = element_text(color = "black"), legend.title = element_blank()) +
  annotate("text", x = 1977, y = 6.5e-05, label = "    R² < 0.001\np = 0.89", size = 6)

lo.reg <- ggplot(reg_data_articles, aes(x = Var1, y = N)) +
  geom_point(size= 1.5) +

  theme_classic(base_size = 15) +
  labs (title = "b)", 
        x= NULL, 
        y= NULL) +
  theme(text = element_text(color = "black"), legend.title = element_blank(), axis.line.y = element_blank(), axis.title.y = element_blank(), axis.ticks.y = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank())

Parasite specialist or generalist nature

In this section we built the graphs illustrating whether the parasites were considered specialist or generalist in literature, plus if we found it infecting more than one host family or host order in this review.

We removed all parasites that were registered only once, since it would inflate the frequency of parasites infecting only one fish family/order. Among all 186 parasite species, 88 were registered only once.

pstyle_plot <- data |> 
  group_by(psp) |> 
  filter(n() > 1) |>        # Keep only species with more than one occurrence
  ungroup() |> 
  group_by(pstyle, psp, ambiguous, N.host.families, N.host.orders) |> 
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    NumberFamilies = case_when(
      N.host.families == 1 ~ factor("One"),
      N.host.families > 1 & N.host.families <= 5 ~ factor("More than one"),
      N.host.families > 5 ~ factor("More than five")
    ),
    NumberOrders = case_when(
      N.host.orders == 1 ~ factor("One"),
      N.host.orders > 1 & N.host.orders <= 5 ~ factor("More than one"),
      N.host.orders > 5 ~ factor("More than five")
    )
  )

Graph for the amount of fish families infected:

nfamilies <- pstyle_plot |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = pstyle, fill = NumberFamilies)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", position = "dodge", color= "black") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 15) +
  scale_fill_tron() +
  scale_y_continuous(

Networks

Sankey diagrams

Sankey diagram for origin and invaded area for spillover parasites

For the Sankey diagram, its needed two data frames, which will have important comments.

1) the first is the count of links between native and invaded countries:

spillover <- data |> 
  filter(
    lab %in% c("No"),
    meltdown %in% c("No"), # Invasion meltdown events (n = 81) were removed, of which 50 are from fishes native to Asia.
    Spillmode == "spillover",
    original.host.continent %in% c("Africa", "Asia", "Europe", "North America", "Oceania", "South America") # There are some parasites and hosts that have a unknown distribution or native range. Some of them had a vast distribution like "northern hemisphere", "Atlantic Ocean", etc. In both cases, that accounted for 109 registers that were removed for this diagram. I accounted only the ones that had a distribution inside the continents.
  ) |> 
  select(
    original.host.continent,
    continent
  ) |> 
  as_tibble()

spillover_links <- spillover |> 
  count(original.host.continent, continent) |> 
  mutate(continent = str_c(continent, " ")) # The spacing is needed, so the invaded and native continents will be different even having the same name.

2) the second is a list of host-parasite connections (which will be the node names):

spillover_nodes <- data.frame(
  nodes = c(
    as.character(spillover_links$original.host.continent), 
    spillover_links$continent
  ) |> 
    unique()
)

spillover_links <- spillover_links |> 
  mutate(
    IDsource = match(spillover_links$original.host.continent, spillover_nodes$nodes)-1,
    IDtarget = match(spillover_links$continent, spillover_nodes$nodes)-1
  )

Plotting the diagram:

sankeyNetwork(Links = spillover_links, Nodes = spillover_nodes,
              Source = "IDsource", Target = "IDtarget",
              Value = "n", NodeID = "nodes", 
              sinksRight = T, nodeWidth = 40, fontSize = 13)
## Links is a tbl_df. Converting to a plain data frame.

Network with ‘bipartite’

Bipartite network for host and parasite species (species-species netwok):

network <- data |> 
  select(horder, pphy, hsp, psp) |> 
  mutate(nothing = "")  # creating an empty column because frame2webs function requires to specify the network community even if I'm working with just one community, and I don't know how to handle this otherwise.
  
network_sp <- frame2webs(network, varnames = c("hsp", "psp", "nothing"), type.out = "array") |> 
  as.data.frame()

Reordering is needed to see the nestedness pattern in the network:

network_sp <- network_sp[order(rowSums(network_sp), decreasing = T), order(colSums(network_sp), decreasing = T)]

Plotting the network:

plotweb(network_sp, method = "normal", y.width.low = 0.05, y.width.high = 0.05, y.lim = c(0, 1.92), arrow = "no", col.low = "black", bor.col.low = "black", col.high = "black", bor.col.high = "black", col.interaction = "grey", bor.col.interaction = "black", high.lablength = 0, low.lablength = 0)

Network with ‘igraph’

This is an one mode projection network. It will show connected host species that share parasite species in common.

First, its needed to set a color for each host species:

node_colors <- paletteer_d("ggsci::default_igv")[0:23] # It's a vector of 23 color codes, one for each host order.

order_colors <- data.frame(
  horder = unique(data$horder), 
  color = node_colors
)

And then join the colors to the dataframe:

data_colors <- data |> 
  left_join(order_colors, join_by(horder))

For the one mode projection for S/DE registers:

# Creating the S/DE network.
spillback_1mode <- data |> 
  filter(Spillmode == "S/DE") |> 
  select(hsp, psp) |> 
  graph_from_data_frame(directed = F)

# It was needed to set this network as a bipartite network
V(spillback_1mode)$type <- bipartite.mapping(spillback_1mode)$type
## Warning: `bipartite.mapping()` was deprecated in igraph 2.0.0.
## ℹ Please use `bipartite_mapping()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
# Then, it was possible to use this function to made a one mode projection. 
# $proj1 is the one mode network for hosts, while $proj2 is for parasites.
proj_spillback <- bipartite.projection(spillback_1mode)$proj1
## Warning: `bipartite.projection()` was deprecated in igraph 2.0.0.
## ℹ Please use `bipartite_projection()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
# Imputing the color for each node
V(proj_spillback)$color <- data_colors$color[match(V(proj_spillback)$name, data_colors$hsp)]

# Setting the layout (from 'qgraph')
lb <- qgraph.layout.fruchtermanreingold(get.edgelist(proj_spillback, names = FALSE), vcount = vcount(proj_spillback), area = 8*(vcount(proj_spillback)^2), repulse.rad = (vcount(proj_spillback)^3.1))
## Warning: `get.edgelist()` was deprecated in igraph 2.0.0.
## ℹ Please use `as_edgelist()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
plot(proj_spillback, layout = lb, vertex.label.color = "black", vertex.size = 3, vertex.label = NA)

For the one mode projection for spillover registers:

# Creating the spillover network.
spillover_1mode <- data |> 
  filter(Spillmode == "spillover") |> 
  select(hsp, psp) |> 
  graph_from_data_frame(directed = F)

# Exactly the same things done for S/DE will be done in here for spillover

proj_spillover <- bipartite.projection(spillover_1mode)$proj1

V(proj_spillover)$color <- data_colors$color[match(V(proj_spillover)$name, data_colors$hsp)]

lo <- qgraph.layout.fruchtermanreingold(get.edgelist(proj_spillover, names = FALSE), vcount = vcount(proj_spillover), area = 8*(vcount(proj_spillover)^2), repulse.rad = (vcount(proj_spillover)^3.1))

plot(proj_spillover, layout = lo, vertex.label.color = "black", vertex.size = 3, vertex.label = NA)

Network metrics

This was the code used to find the network indexes described for the full network (with S/DE and spillover events), for host and parasite species:

data |> 
  select(hsp, psp) |> 
  mutate(nothing = "") |> 
  frame2webs(varnames = c("hsp", "psp", "nothing"), type.out = "array") |> 
  as.data.frame() |> 
  networklevel(index = "ALL")

World map

The world countries shape was downloaded from >http://tapiquen-sig.jimdo.com< Carlos Efraín Porto Tapiquén. Orogénesis Soluciones Geográficas. Porlamar, Venezuela 2015. Based on shapes from Enviromental Systems Research Institute (ESRI). Free Distribuition.

Reading the shape file:

countries <- read_sf("World_Countries.shp")
countries$COUNTRY[countries$COUNTRY == "New Caledonia (France)"] <- "New Caledonia" # just adjusting this country name

Changing some country names in my dataset so it will fit with the “countries” object:

data_map <- data  |> 
  mutate(country = gsub("USA", "United States", country)) |> 
  mutate(country = gsub("(England|Scotland|Wales|Ireland|Isle of Man)", "United Kingdom", country)) |> 
  rename(COUNTRY = country) |> 
  filter(COUNTRY != "Not applicable")

Percent of invasion registers per country (Supplementary material 3):

data_map  |>
  group_by(COUNTRY)  |> 
  summarise(n = n())  |> 
  mutate(percent = n / sum(n) * 100) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(COUNTRY, percent), y = percent)) +
  geom_col(color = "black", fill = "darkred") +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Registers percent") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, 25)) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw(base_size = 15)

Percent of spillmode by country:

spillcount <- data_map |>  
  count(Spillmode, COUNTRY) |> 
  group_by(COUNTRY) |> 
  mutate(percent = n / sum(n) * 100)

country_coords <- countries |>
  full_join(spillcount, join_by(COUNTRY)) |> 
  mutate(
    n = ifelse(is.na(n), 0, n),
    percent = ifelse(is.na(percent), 0, percent)
  )

Taking the coordinates for the center of each country (which will be the piechart positions)

centroids <- st_centroid(country_coords$geometry)
country_coords$lat <- st_coordinates(centroids)[,2]
country_coords$long <- st_coordinates(centroids)[,1]

country_coords <- country_coords |> 
  mutate(
    lat = ifelse(COUNTRY == "United States", 38.5, lat), # Adjusting the USA and Canada coordinates was needed, so the piechart is displayied the center +
    long = ifelse(COUNTRY == "United States", -95.7129, long),
    lat = ifelse(COUNTRY == "Canada", 59.4371435, lat),
    long = ifelse(COUNTRY == "Canada", -105, long),
    cumsum = ave(n, Spillmode, FUN = cumsum), # Adding the cummulative sum and total sum of the number of registers
    total = ave(n, Spillmode, FUN = sum),
    start = 2 * pi * cumsum(percent) / 100 - 2 * pi * percent / 100, # Adding the start and end points of the charts.
    end = 2 * pi * cumsum(percent) / 100,
    sum_n = ave(n, COUNTRY, FUN = sum)
  )

Plotting the map for amunt of records:

map_records <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = country_coords, fill = "white") +
  geom_arc_bar(
    data = filter(country_coords, !is.na(Spillmode)), 
    aes(x0 = long, y0 = lat, r0 = 0, r = 1.5*log(sum_n+1),
        start = start,
        end = end,
        fill = Spillmode), 
    alpha = 0.7
  ) +
  scale_fill_jco(guide = guide_legend(nrow = 1)) +
  theme_void(base_size = 15) +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = NULL)) +
  labs(subtitle = "       A)")

Organizing data for plotting the world map with species number:

spillcount2 <- data_map |>  
  group_by(COUNTRY, psp, Spillmode) |> 
  summarise(n = n(), .groups = "drop") |> 
  group_by(COUNTRY, Spillmode) |> 
  summarise(n = n(), .groups = "drop") |> 
  group_by(COUNTRY) |> 
  mutate(percent = n / sum(n) * 100) |> 
  ungroup()

country_coords2 <- countries |>
  full_join(spillcount2, join_by(COUNTRY)) |> 
  mutate(
    n = ifelse(is.na(n), 0, n),
    percent = ifelse(is.na(percent), 0, percent)
  )

centroids2 <- st_centroid(country_coords2$geometry)
country_coords2$lat <- st_coordinates(centroids2)[,2]
country_coords2$long <- st_coordinates(centroids2)[,1]

country_coords2 <- country_coords2 |> 
  mutate(
    lat = ifelse(COUNTRY == "United States", 38.5, lat),
    long = ifelse(COUNTRY == "United States", -95.7129, long),
    lat = ifelse(COUNTRY == "Canada", 59.4371435, lat),
    long = ifelse(COUNTRY == "Canada", -105, long),
    cumsum = ave(n, Spillmode, FUN = cumsum),
    total = ave(n, Spillmode, FUN = sum),
    start = 2 * pi * cumsum(percent) / 100 - 2 * pi * percent / 100,
    end = 2 * pi * cumsum(percent) / 100,
    sum_n = ave(n, COUNTRY, FUN = sum)
  ) 

map_species <- ggplot() +
